1
00:00:03,742 --> 00:00:10,253
Tonight I'd like to look at the exercises for mindfulness of breath given in the Satipatthana Sutta.

2
00:00:11,916 --> 00:00:17,303
Satipatthana usually translates as a foundation or support for mindfulness.

3
00:00:18,926 --> 00:00:27,861
Joseph Goldstein also suggests the word pasture, a fertile field where attention can safely graze.

4
00:00:29,106 --> 00:00:30,748
I like that pastoral image.

5
00:00:31,670 --> 00:00:35,814
It suggests a restful approach as an antidote to our habitual striving.

6
00:00:37,277 --> 00:00:43,844
There are four satipatthana, body, feeling, mind and dhammas.

7
00:00:44,987 --> 00:00:47,590
The last one covers the main teachings of the Buddha.

8
00:00:50,613 --> 00:00:57,341
The first satipatthana, where mindfulness explores the posture of the body, starts with the breath.

9
00:00:58,299 --> 00:00:59,240
Here's the passage.

10
00:01:02,084 --> 00:01:09,031
Having gone to the forest, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, one sits down.

11
00:01:10,451 --> 00:01:23,245
Having folded one's legs crosswise, set the body erect, and established mindfulness in front of one, ever mindful one breathes in, mindful one breathes out.

12
00:01:24,102 --> 00:01:29,049
Breathing in long, one understands I breathe in long.

13
00:01:30,250 --> 00:01:35,096
Or breathing out long, one understands I breathe out long.

14
00:01:36,337 --> 00:01:41,405
Breathing in short, one understands I breathe in short.

15
00:01:42,225 --> 00:01:48,995
Or breathing out short, one understands I breathe out short.

16
00:01:49,015 --> 00:01:53,721
One trains thus, I shall breathe in experiencing the whole body.

17
00:01:55,287 --> 00:02:00,875
One trains thus, I shall breathe out experiencing the whole body.

18
00:02:02,656 --> 00:02:07,623
One trains thus, I shall breathe in tranquilizing the bodily formation.

19
00:02:09,286 --> 00:02:14,393
One trains thus, I shall breathe out tranquilizing the bodily formation.

20
00:02:16,076 --> 00:02:23,705
Just as a skilled turner or their apprentice, when making a long turn, understands, I make a long turn.

21
00:02:23,746 --> 00:02:28,951
Or when making a short turn, one understands, I make a short turn.

22
00:02:30,253 --> 00:02:35,419
So too, breathing in long, one understands, I breathe in long.

23
00:02:36,760 --> 00:02:40,806
Or breathing out long, one understands, I breathe out long.

24
00:02:41,627 --> 00:02:44,430
And so on for all the following exercises.

25
00:02:47,312 --> 00:02:56,687
The first few sentences clarify that this is formal practice, not simply relaxation or a distraction for a few moments when we've nothing better to do.

26
00:02:57,949 --> 00:03:06,401
We're making time in life specifically for this practice, going somewhere secluded and taking care with our sitting posture.

27
00:03:06,382 --> 00:03:18,551
The phrase, established mindfulness in front of one, can be taken to mean that we've clarified for ourselves that our job is to be mindful, to attend to present moment experience.

28
00:03:20,506 --> 00:03:24,272
Having done all that, we focus on the experience of breathing.

29
00:03:25,215 --> 00:03:26,657
Mindful, one breathes in.

30
00:03:27,639 --> 00:03:29,242
Mindful, one breathes out.

31
00:03:30,485 --> 00:03:38,379
This is our usual starting point for Vipassana, bringing attention into the body, into the sensations that accompany breathing.

32
00:03:41,465 --> 00:03:50,717
When the mind has steadied, the next step in the Mahasi approach is to broaden awareness, allowing attention rest wherever it is called.

33
00:03:52,281 --> 00:03:58,830
To follow the Satipatthana approach, we instead take up one or other of the exercises suggested here.

34
00:04:00,331 --> 00:04:01,693
This could get confusing.

35
00:04:02,695 --> 00:04:05,699
Should I be practicing Mahasi or Satipatthana?

36
00:04:06,962 --> 00:04:14,835
The same question could be asked of the exercises in any other parts of the Satipatthana Sutta, Feeling, Mind, Dhamma.

37
00:04:17,499 --> 00:04:22,065
The Satipatthana exercises are more challenging than normal Mahasi practice.

38
00:04:23,307 --> 00:04:28,235
They often show up some unacknowledged attachment, tweak our understanding.

39
00:04:29,817 --> 00:04:32,341
However, we can't push ourselves too far.

40
00:04:33,642 --> 00:04:36,226
We have to let any new understanding integrate.

41
00:04:37,523 --> 00:04:45,814
We do that by reverting back to our normal Mahasi practice as we work through whatever hindrances have been stirred by the exercise.

42
00:04:48,517 --> 00:04:59,632
My advice, therefore, is to clarify that Mahasi is our basic practice and that we only take up one of these exercises on occasion as a means of tweaking our practice.

43
00:05:01,148 --> 00:05:15,968
The moment we feel ourselves straining or getting dull or distracted or confused, we immediately go back to the Mahasi approach, allowing attention go wherever it is called, letting go of any attempt to follow the Satipatthana exercise.

44
00:05:19,019 --> 00:05:24,845
This is especially important because most of us are influenced by modern culture of individual achievement.

45
00:05:25,685 --> 00:05:32,672
And so we turn these Satipatthana exercises into another arena where we have to achieve, become expert.

46
00:05:33,812 --> 00:05:46,225
To counteract this, we must be willing to revert to the more straightforward Mahasi approach whenever we feel ourselves coming under pressure, trying to get the exercise right, trying to do things perfectly.

47
00:05:47,673 --> 00:05:53,451
We can see all this as purifying our addiction to achievement and therefore very beneficial.

48
00:05:56,639 --> 00:06:00,552
So please keep that in mind throughout the rest of the talk.

49
00:06:00,699 --> 00:06:04,064
Our principal aim is to be mindful without any interference.

50
00:06:05,386 --> 00:06:20,165
The Satipatthana exercise are only used when things go quiet and we're feeling the breath anyhow as part of Mahasi practice and we feel steady enough to give ourselves a challenge, tweak our practice in the right direction.

51
00:06:23,288 --> 00:06:26,572
Having said all that, let's look at the first exercise.

52
00:06:28,341 --> 00:06:34,209
When we notice ourselves taking in a long breath, we understand, I breathe in long.

53
00:06:35,531 --> 00:06:38,714
The Buddha doesn't ask us to deliberately take in a long breath.

54
00:06:39,536 --> 00:06:40,658
We're breathing naturally.

55
00:06:41,899 --> 00:06:48,567
It's only when we notice that the in or out breath is unusually long or short that we reflect in this way.

56
00:06:49,908 --> 00:06:54,535
Attachment to breathing symbolizes attachment to life itself.

57
00:06:56,692 --> 00:06:59,314
Without this vital movement we quickly die.

58
00:07:02,177 --> 00:07:07,725
When we're breathing with long deep breaths there's often a sense of ease and satisfaction.

59
00:07:09,887 --> 00:07:20,639
But attachment can add to this with delight, with pride, with the habit of fanaticizing and making great plans on the basis of feeling good.

60
00:07:23,319 --> 00:07:28,726
We can't get too carried away with those when we're noting that the breath is longer than usual.

61
00:07:30,629 --> 00:07:38,158
Thus the exercise keeps us grounded in the body, prevents us drifting into a cloud of hazy delight and delusion.

62
00:07:40,141 --> 00:07:45,548
Sometimes a long breath is from a sigh or yawn that preludes sleepiness.

63
00:07:47,148 --> 00:07:56,108
In this case, noting, I breathe in or out long, helps keep us awake, alert to these signs of drowsiness.

64
00:08:00,098 --> 00:08:05,612
When the breath is shallow and rapid, there is often some negativity behind this.

65
00:08:05,726 --> 00:08:09,771
For example, fear can make for a jerky, uncomfortable breath.

66
00:08:11,153 --> 00:08:13,175
Anxiety can make the breath shallow and rapid.

67
00:08:14,416 --> 00:08:18,341
Anger might tense the body so that we take short, forced breaths.

68
00:08:20,283 --> 00:08:25,529
Often we're so fixated on the thoughts driving the emotion, we hardly notice the breath.

69
00:08:27,271 --> 00:08:32,577
Here, we're being asked to deliberately reflect that we're taking short breaths in and out.

70
00:08:34,211 --> 00:08:44,106
This takes some attention away from the thought fixation, might show us underlying aversion, desire or emotional turmoil.

71
00:08:44,147 --> 00:08:54,623
Note there's no judgment involved in this exercise, no preference that the breath be long rather than short.

72
00:08:56,044 --> 00:09:01,653
Our only job is to know when it becomes unusually long or unusually short.

73
00:09:03,169 --> 00:09:12,166
The exercise makes us more aware of how emotions affect the breath, grounds attention in the body while the emotion is passing through.

74
00:09:15,110 --> 00:09:19,438
Remember that at any point we can go back to our usual Mahasi practice.

75
00:09:20,822 --> 00:09:26,611
We note whatever predominantly calls attention, let the breath go at its own pace.

76
00:09:28,785 --> 00:09:33,309
We stop asking ourselves whether it's going in or out, whether it's long or short.

77
00:09:34,270 --> 00:09:42,960
Tracking the emotion mindfully is to purify our attachment to breathing or to doing the exercise properly or whatever has stirred us up.

78
00:09:46,023 --> 00:09:55,451
The next exercise is described as training, as opposed to our usual approach in Vipassana, which is to be mindful without having any agenda.

79
00:09:57,928 --> 00:10:02,735
One trains thus, I shall breathe in experiencing the full body.

80
00:10:04,355 --> 00:10:07,159
I shall breathe out experiencing the full body.

81
00:10:09,923 --> 00:10:14,548
Sometimes the full body is interpreted as the full body of the breath.

82
00:10:15,870 --> 00:10:20,595
For instance, we track beginning, middle and end of the breath.

83
00:10:22,076 --> 00:10:29,508
Another interpretation is that we have a broad awareness of the full body, with the breath as one component within this.

84
00:10:31,451 --> 00:10:33,934
I find the second interpretation more helpful.

85
00:10:35,537 --> 00:10:41,605
Instead of focusing closely on the sensations of breathing, we have a more spacious awareness of the body.

86
00:10:46,133 --> 00:10:49,738
It's interesting that this exercise is described as training.

87
00:10:51,541 --> 00:10:56,513
The natural tendency is for mindfulness to focus down on one sensation or another.

88
00:10:58,236 --> 00:11:01,364
We have to put some effort into maintaining the more spacious approach.

89
00:11:03,850 --> 00:11:09,582
The teacher Rob Berbia describes it as blowing up a bubble of mindfulness.

90
00:11:11,065 --> 00:11:24,357
whenever we notice the bubble deflating and attention closing down onto some particular sensation then we very gently blow up that bubble again so that mindfulness encompasses the full body.

91
00:11:28,041 --> 00:11:32,225
The point of this training is to help us develop a more spacious awareness.

92
00:11:34,947 --> 00:11:37,090
This can at times be very useful

93
00:11:38,740 --> 00:11:46,125
We can get lost in detail, overly delighted by pleasant feelings for example, fearful around unpleasant ones.

94
00:11:48,048 --> 00:11:54,913
This is no problem when we have enough equanimity to remain mindful and objective despite these strong emotions.

95
00:11:56,835 --> 00:12:03,061
However, when we feel ourselves being overwhelmed by emotion, it can be helpful to broaden awareness.

96
00:12:05,722 --> 00:12:08,325
This promotes objectivity and equanimity

97
00:12:09,418 --> 00:12:13,605
lets the emotion burn away without overwhelming us completely.

98
00:12:17,032 --> 00:12:28,913
This exercise to breathe in experiencing the full body, breathe out experiencing the full body, develops our ability to stand back, see the bigger picture.

99
00:12:31,035 --> 00:12:42,365
If we deliberately practice this from time to time we'll find it creeping naturally into our Vipassana practice when we're being threatened with overwhelm and need to strengthen equanimity.

100
00:12:46,750 --> 00:12:49,793
The next instruction also involves training.

101
00:12:51,595 --> 00:12:56,399
One trains thus I shall breathe in tranquilizing the bodily formation.

102
00:12:57,980 --> 00:12:59,642
One trains thus

103
00:13:00,347 --> 00:13:03,413
I shall breathe out, tranquilizing the bodily formation.

104
00:13:07,039 --> 00:13:09,845
The Pali word for formation is Sankara.

105
00:13:12,789 --> 00:13:20,322
We're more used to thinking of Sankara in terms of the mind, the habits of mind we develop every time we think, speak or act.

106
00:13:21,686 --> 00:13:23,688
But there are also habits of body.

107
00:13:24,951 --> 00:13:26,573
Each of us walks in our own way.

108
00:13:27,816 --> 00:13:31,100
Our posture and facial expression are likewise individuated.

109
00:13:32,741 --> 00:13:38,489
Every time we frown, our facial muscles get another chance to perfect their ability to frown.

110
00:13:39,990 --> 00:13:42,913
Thus our physical makeup is based on habit.

111
00:13:47,200 --> 00:13:52,966
When we tranquilize the bodily formation, we are allowing the breath to calm the body

112
00:13:55,917 --> 00:14:01,001
We might be amazed at how much tension we hold until we consciously try to relax.

113
00:14:02,143 --> 00:14:10,131
The face, the jaw, the shoulders, the stomach, all these can hold knots of tension.

114
00:14:12,833 --> 00:14:14,355
The habit of tension runs deep.

115
00:14:15,496 --> 00:14:18,941
As soon as we relax a muscle, we might notice it's tensing up again.

116
00:14:20,581 --> 00:14:23,325
That's why this instruction is also a form of training.

117
00:14:25,398 --> 00:14:32,807
We're cultivating a new habit, trying to teach an old dog tricks and we have to have a lot of patience.

118
00:14:38,794 --> 00:14:48,466
Many people have practical challenges such as financial pressure, ill health, deadlines at work, relationship difficulties.

119
00:14:50,349 --> 00:14:52,451
All these can result in physical tension.

120
00:14:54,456 --> 00:14:59,682
Even if there are no obvious challenges, we carry stress because of our unenlightened nature.

121
00:15:01,105 --> 00:15:03,126
We keep expecting the world to make us happy.

122
00:15:04,548 --> 00:15:09,634
If only we could get away on holiday, get a pay rise, be more confident.

123
00:15:10,554 --> 00:15:11,976
Surely then we would be happy.

124
00:15:13,958 --> 00:15:15,801
But the world cannot satisfy.

125
00:15:17,003 --> 00:15:20,986
Life is dukkha, the Buddha proclaims in the First Noble Truth.

126
00:15:22,333 --> 00:15:28,001
No job, relationship or achievement can provide a secure basis for happiness.

127
00:15:30,044 --> 00:15:33,890
All of these are unstable, changing, unreliable.

128
00:15:36,455 --> 00:15:39,879
To be deluded is to be constantly disappointed.

129
00:15:42,283 --> 00:15:45,687
Retreating into cynicism or hopelessness is no help either.

130
00:15:47,070 --> 00:15:49,033
Life has its ups as well as downs.

131
00:15:50,465 --> 00:15:52,888
We cannot prevent pleasant feelings registering.

132
00:15:54,070 --> 00:16:00,457
To maintain cynicism, we have to tense up to suppress the smidgen of joy and hope that follows each one.

133
00:16:03,942 --> 00:16:07,427
The exercise of relaxing the body can therefore be challenging.

134
00:16:09,129 --> 00:16:15,577
We are asking ourselves to trust that, at least for now, for this meditation session, there is no need to worry.

135
00:16:16,519 --> 00:16:17,561
We are in a safe place.

136
00:16:18,682 --> 00:16:21,547
We have nothing to achieve apart from remaining mindful.

137
00:16:24,071 --> 00:16:26,453
The instruction links relaxation with the breath.

138
00:16:28,736 --> 00:16:31,561
I shall breathe in tranquilizing the body formation.

139
00:16:32,982 --> 00:16:35,726
I shall breathe out tranquilizing the body formation.

140
00:16:39,149 --> 00:16:47,059
The Vipassana teacher Bhante Sujeeva suggests imagining the breath flowing through whichever part of the body we are relaxing.

141
00:16:48,822 --> 00:16:53,288
We could even imagine a wave of breath flowing the whole full length of the body.

142
00:16:55,692 --> 00:16:57,495
But we can't force relaxation.

143
00:16:58,792 --> 00:17:10,484
If tension gets even tighter as we think about relaxing, then we need to let go of the exercise, go back to Mahasi practice, feel the tension as sensations, without judging these as wrong.

144
00:17:12,467 --> 00:17:17,192
This is to give the underlying emotion the time and space it needs to be acknowledged.

145
00:17:22,178 --> 00:17:25,862
The Buddha gives the simile of a woodturner for our work with the breath.

146
00:17:27,664 --> 00:17:40,048
Just as a skilled turner or their apprentice, when making a long turn, understands, I make a long turn, so too breathing in long, one understands, I breathe in long.

147
00:17:41,430 --> 00:17:49,925
He is saying that we are to regard breathing as a skill, one that needs devoted practice, an activity we can respect and esteem.

148
00:17:51,761 --> 00:18:05,095
James, who is one of Bhante's students, who is a skilled woodworker, sent me a video of a man carving out an ornate chess set using a traditional instrument similar to those used in the Buddha's day.

149
00:18:06,736 --> 00:18:10,799
One hand turns a bow which determines how quickly the wood spins.

150
00:18:11,601 --> 00:18:18,326
The other hand, or sometimes a foot, holds a blade that cuts into the spinning wood, carving out a pattern.

151
00:18:19,428 --> 00:18:21,329
It really is an impressive skill.

152
00:18:23,385 --> 00:18:29,773
With a sharp knife in one hand and a delicate bow in another, the turner has to be very alert to what he is doing.

153
00:18:31,596 --> 00:18:34,299
Would it be possible to see the breath in a similar fashion?

154
00:18:37,423 --> 00:18:47,757
Long slow breaths help us relax, gain stability, resource ourselves, while rapid breathing often accompanies emotional release.

155
00:18:49,204 --> 00:18:55,192
Rather than preferring one to the other, could we, like the woodturner, learn to see which was appropriate?

156
00:18:56,473 --> 00:19:00,539
At times we take long, slow breaths with flow throughout the body.

157
00:19:02,162 --> 00:19:05,205
These steady the mind, promote equanimity.

158
00:19:07,409 --> 00:19:13,997
At times the breath grows short and rapid, as strong tensions emerge along with a storm of emotion.

159
00:19:15,631 --> 00:19:25,887
If awareness can track the physical sensations, we feel the underlying emotion more objectively, allowing old fears and grudges heal.

160
00:19:29,153 --> 00:19:39,951
Just as the woodturner carves out a beautiful shape from rough wood, so mindfulness of breath carves out wisdom from raw physical sensations.

161
00:19:44,133 --> 00:19:49,260
We have to be careful that the emphasis on skill doesn't lead to the wrong attitude.

162
00:19:50,663 --> 00:19:58,595
We might start getting uptight, putting ourselves under pressure to have the perfect yogic breath or to release all our fears and phobias.

163
00:19:59,977 --> 00:20:01,439
But this is to cultivate dukkha.

164
00:20:03,102 --> 00:20:05,965
In truth, we are not in control of the breath.

165
00:20:07,808 --> 00:20:09,971
Any semblance of control is delusion.

166
00:20:12,567 --> 00:20:25,127
It's only when we can surrender, allow the breath to come and go, just as nature intends, that we find ourselves in tune, that the breath follows the pattern we also think is best.

167
00:20:27,791 --> 00:20:31,317
Training ourselves to breathe mindfully is a humbling process.

168
00:20:33,053 --> 00:20:45,529
To help ourselves through these times, we can remember that the Buddha's analogy also includes the apprentice, just as a skilled woodturner or his apprentice were to make a long turn.

169
00:20:47,472 --> 00:20:54,942
The Buddha gives us full permission to be the apprentice, having barely a clue how to get a breath into tight lungs.

170
00:20:57,521 --> 00:21:04,233
Having described these exercises for mindfulness of breath, we then come to what is termed the refrain of the Sutta.

171
00:21:05,936 --> 00:21:12,489
The Buddha repeats this refrain after each set of exercises in all four Satipatthana.

172
00:21:14,333 --> 00:21:19,362
Here is how it goes for the first Satipatthana, mindfulness of body.

173
00:21:20,522 --> 00:21:36,152
In this way, he abides contemplating the body as a body internally, or he abides contemplating the body as a body externally, or else he abides contemplating the body in its arising factors.

174
00:21:36,132 --> 00:21:39,734
Or he abides contemplating the body in its vanishing factors.

175
00:21:40,935 --> 00:21:45,480
Or he abides contemplating the body in its arising and vanishing factors.

176
00:21:46,580 --> 00:21:55,429
Or else mindfulness that there is a body is simply established in him to the extent necessary for bare knowledge and mindfulness.

177
00:21:56,691 --> 00:22:00,534
And he abides independent, not clinging to anything in the world.

178
00:22:01,914 --> 00:22:06,138
That is how a bhikkhu abides contemplating the body as a body.

179
00:22:07,991 --> 00:22:13,021
Contemplating the body as a body internally is what we've been describing so far.

180
00:22:13,864 --> 00:22:17,049
We're looking inside, feeling our own sensations.

181
00:22:18,432 --> 00:22:20,616
It's interesting that this is called contemplating.

182
00:22:21,878 --> 00:22:23,722
To contemplate is to think deeply.

183
00:22:25,025 --> 00:22:27,891
We're not actively generating thoughts as we practice.

184
00:22:28,933 --> 00:22:32,979
But the mind that can think is present, part of the watching process.

185
00:22:34,280 --> 00:22:39,086
It's taking in information, much as though we were at a lecture or watching a documentary.

186
00:22:40,628 --> 00:22:44,673
We might notice that the jaw tenses when we come to the end of the out-breath, for example.

187
00:22:46,457 --> 00:22:55,228
Even if this isn't processed into a grammatical sentence, the facts of the matter are now known and will make us more aware of our jaw tensing in daily life.

188
00:22:56,255 --> 00:23:04,402
Thus, mindfulness of breath is a form of deep thought, of contemplating the body, seeing how it works, what habits we're following.

189
00:23:08,125 --> 00:23:13,970
To contemplate the body externally is normally interpreted as becoming mindful of other people's bodies.

190
00:23:15,131 --> 00:23:19,875
In the case of these breathing exercises, we are to be mindful of others' breathing.

191
00:23:21,296 --> 00:23:26,160
This is quite a challenge, but it may be possible to make a start here on retreat

192
00:23:26,983 --> 00:23:33,152
If another person's breathing is quite loud, we can easily detect when they're breathing in and when they're breathing out.

193
00:23:34,193 --> 00:23:38,400
And this might also help diminish any irritation that could otherwise develop.

194
00:23:39,862 --> 00:23:42,545
After all, at least now they're helping us concentrate.

195
00:23:44,748 --> 00:23:48,073
At times, of course, it could make the irritation even more acute.

196
00:23:48,834 --> 00:23:50,375
But again, that's helpful.

197
00:23:51,778 --> 00:23:56,163
We often have a false expectation that meditation should be pleasant, peaceful.

198
00:23:57,190 --> 00:23:59,973
noisy breathing can therefore seem an outrage.

199
00:24:01,076 --> 00:24:09,608
But of course our expectation is the real problem, and so we have an opportunity to work with the anger or sadness that follows dashed expectations.

200
00:24:11,050 --> 00:24:23,028
Going back to the woodturner analogy, we could regard this work as carving our body and mind into a new shape, one that fits in more easily with all the unpleasant stuff life dumps on our plate.

201
00:24:26,484 --> 00:24:30,489
Sometimes the noisy breath goes quiet, just as we're getting interested in it.

202
00:24:32,111 --> 00:24:37,355
An alternative would then be to reflect that others breathe in and out just as we ourselves do.

203
00:24:38,538 --> 00:24:44,604
Feeling the sensations of breath in our own body, we reflect that those around us are feeling similar sensations.

204
00:24:46,226 --> 00:24:53,353
We can take this through all the exercises, reflecting that others breathe in long, breathe out long, and so on.

205
00:24:54,463 --> 00:24:59,250
We can, in our imagination, calm their body as they breathe in and out.

206
00:25:02,355 --> 00:25:05,640
This is a form of meta-practice.

207
00:25:05,660 --> 00:25:09,244
We're taking others into our imagination at quite an intimate level.

208
00:25:11,327 --> 00:25:19,459
It can stir a feeling of friendliness and connection, perhaps even confidence, to know that we're not actually so very different to others.

209
00:25:21,650 --> 00:25:23,291
It can also show up attachment.

210
00:25:24,134 --> 00:25:25,976
We're all deeply attached to the breath.

211
00:25:27,018 --> 00:25:28,259
It means life after all.

212
00:25:29,801 --> 00:25:36,471
At some level we're holding to the pleasant feeling associated with being able to breathe, thinking of this as mine.

213
00:25:38,574 --> 00:25:42,460
This exercise asks us to imagine the feeling as also being in others.

214
00:25:45,021 --> 00:25:52,896
When attachment is showing up, we might feel deeply threatened, like we're being robbed of our own breath and of life itself.

215
00:25:54,980 --> 00:26:05,460
If we can bear with whatever emotions surface while we do the exercise, this is an opportunity for us to work with what is possibly the deepest attachment in life.

216
00:26:10,164 --> 00:26:16,976
The refrain then presents the option of contemplating the body in its arising factors.

217
00:26:21,403 --> 00:26:24,127
We know the body through physical sensations.

218
00:26:26,372 --> 00:26:28,055
No sensation lasts forever.

219
00:26:29,817 --> 00:26:33,202
Each one arises at some moment and then passes away.

220
00:26:35,461 --> 00:26:41,469
To contemplate the arising factors, we attend to the first moment we become aware of sensations.

221
00:26:43,191 --> 00:26:46,434
Tuning into the start of the in-breath is a good way to do this.

222
00:26:48,037 --> 00:26:57,789
The body relaxes after the out-breath and then at some moment the tissues start moving and we feel the abdomen or chest starting to swell.

223
00:26:59,473 --> 00:27:10,259
Having detected the first moment of in-breath, it may become apparent that the rest of the breath is also composed of sensations that arise one after the other.

224
00:27:12,063 --> 00:27:18,698
We're getting used to the idea of the body as a series of sensations coming into consciousness.

225
00:27:22,306 --> 00:27:32,876
Similarly, we contemplate the body in its vanishing factors when we notice that each of these sensations fades out a moment after it registers.

226
00:27:35,299 --> 00:27:38,564
One way to do this is to follow the out-breath till it stops.

227
00:27:40,164 --> 00:27:41,707
The chest or abdomen deflates.

228
00:27:43,209 --> 00:27:50,135
Sensations grow fainter till eventually no movement is detected, just stillness.

229
00:27:51,819 --> 00:27:55,846
having detected that last sensation fading into stillness.

230
00:27:56,988 --> 00:28:02,596
We are more able to see the breath as sensations fading away, one after the other.

231
00:28:04,941 --> 00:28:11,751
Next, the Buddha gives the option to contemplate the body in its arising and vanishing factors.

232
00:28:13,253 --> 00:28:18,182
As you can imagine, we are now tracking sensations as both arising and fading.

233
00:28:19,916 --> 00:28:23,782
Can we tune into both the start of the in-breath and its end?

234
00:28:25,365 --> 00:28:27,167
The start of the out-breath and its end?

235
00:28:29,270 --> 00:28:33,336
This can be quite a challenge as the feeling is so different for starting and ending.

236
00:28:34,838 --> 00:28:38,064
It takes quite a degree of equanimity to embrace both.

237
00:28:40,006 --> 00:28:44,472
Like all satipatthana exercises, strong emotions can be stirred.

238
00:28:47,557 --> 00:28:52,202
The point of all these exercises, remember, is to help us see through delusion.

239
00:28:53,503 --> 00:28:55,806
The exercise is only a means to that end.

240
00:28:57,268 --> 00:29:08,720
As soon as we start getting uptight, wanting to see the start or end of the breath more clearly, we need to relax, acknowledge whatever emotions might be building up, let them blow off steam.

241
00:29:09,980 --> 00:29:11,962
This is the purification process.

242
00:29:14,676 --> 00:29:19,324
Any emotions stirred during mindfulness of breathing need to be treated with respect.

243
00:29:21,186 --> 00:29:31,344
We've been taking the breath for granted all our lives and it cuts deep to be shown how little control we actually have over this vital bodily function.

244
00:29:33,507 --> 00:29:41,680
We might feel small or stupid not to be able to do something so seemingly simple as feel the breath flowing in and out.

245
00:29:43,819 --> 00:29:49,886
But the mind holds tight to symbols and deep down the breath symbolizes life.

246
00:29:52,130 --> 00:30:01,060
At some level we are all aware that there will sometime come a breath that flows out as normal but is not followed by an in-breath.

247
00:30:03,242 --> 00:30:09,590
It's not surprising therefore that tracking the breath from start to finish can stir all kinds of emotion.

248
00:30:10,836 --> 00:30:14,361
When this happens, remember, we abandon the exercise.

249
00:30:15,262 --> 00:30:17,424
Go back to standard Mahasi practice.

250
00:30:20,028 --> 00:30:22,892
The final option is akin to Mahasi practice.

251
00:30:24,673 --> 00:30:26,215
The Buddha phrases it like this.

252
00:30:27,978 --> 00:30:37,349
Or else, mindfulness that there is a body is simply established in him to the extent necessary for bare knowledge and mindfulness.

253
00:30:38,443 --> 00:30:42,809
and he abides independent, not clinging to anything in the world.

254
00:30:46,394 --> 00:30:53,084
We're no longer trying to detect the beginning or end of the breath, nor trying to follow another person's breathing.

255
00:30:54,545 --> 00:30:59,412
We're not asked to register whether we're breathing in and out, whether the breath is long or short.

256
00:31:01,054 --> 00:31:03,237
It's a more relaxed form of practice.

257
00:31:04,667 --> 00:31:06,849
As in Mahasi, we've no agenda.

258
00:31:07,631 --> 00:31:09,573
We're not interfering in any way.

259
00:31:11,134 --> 00:31:13,076
However, we are to reflect.

260
00:31:13,876 --> 00:31:14,678
There is a body.

261
00:31:16,660 --> 00:31:22,645
This grounds attention in the body, while making the body as a whole the object of meditation.

262
00:31:26,750 --> 00:31:34,117
Just as we're attached to the breath without being aware of this, we can also be attached to the body without being aware of this.

263
00:31:35,734 --> 00:31:46,792
The reflection, there is a body, makes us see the body objectively, cuts across our usual habit of taking it for granted, assuming it's ours.

264
00:31:48,896 --> 00:31:59,835
At times the objectivity brings up gratitude toward this amazing, warm, sensitive entity that ferries us around, lets us see and hear and taste and speak.

265
00:32:01,672 --> 00:32:10,324
At other times we get uncomfortable, want to go back to our habitual assumptions that the body is mine to move around and command at will.

266
00:32:11,926 --> 00:32:22,801
Seeing it as something else, something out there in the world, can become confusing or irritating or sad or perhaps frightening.

267
00:32:25,397 --> 00:32:43,121
Whenever any strong emotions or feelings are evoked we recognize these as part of the purification process and return to our normal Mahasi practice allowing the emotion develop and express itself teaching us the Dhamma as it burns itself out.

268
00:32:47,246 --> 00:32:54,695
In summary then, the Satipatthana Sutta gives us a number of specific exercises relating to the breath.

269
00:32:56,059 --> 00:32:59,643
The first is to steady ourselves with mindfulness of breathing.

270
00:33:00,943 --> 00:33:02,625
Mindful, one breathes in.

271
00:33:03,646 --> 00:33:05,428
Mindful, one breathes out.

272
00:33:06,829 --> 00:33:16,699
We're also asked to reflect, I breathe in or out long, when we notice ourselves taking a long slow breath and similarly for short breaths.

273
00:33:20,582 --> 00:33:23,805
Two training exercises are described.

274
00:33:23,988 --> 00:33:31,059
training ourselves to experience the full body as we breathe in or out, calming the body as we breathe in or out.

275
00:33:32,603 --> 00:33:38,573
The Buddha gives the analogy of the woodturner, indicating that we should respect breathing as a skill.

276
00:33:39,815 --> 00:33:49,371
He kindly includes the analogy of the apprentice, for those many times when the breath is demonstrating that it is in reality totally outside of our control.

277
00:33:52,539 --> 00:33:57,384
We normally do these exercises internally, examining our own experience.

278
00:33:59,067 --> 00:34:04,913
The refrain of the Sutta clarifies that it's equally valid to contemplate the breath of others in the same way.

279
00:34:04,952 --> 00:34:10,237
Alternatively, we can examine the transient nature of the breath.

280
00:34:11,460 --> 00:34:17,585
Notice that what we actually experience is a series of sensations, each arising and fading away.

281
00:34:19,152 --> 00:34:34,572
Finally, we have the option of bare attention, a more relaxed form of practice when we're not doing any of these exercises, but reflecting there is a body as a means of working on our relationship with the body.

282
00:34:37,335 --> 00:34:43,222
It is that final option of bare attention that is most akin to our usual Vipassana practice.

283
00:34:44,985 --> 00:34:48,349
In turn, Vipassana allows insight to develop.

284
00:34:50,945 --> 00:34:56,878
A tennis player will occasionally do special exercises, for example, to strengthen their backhand.

285
00:34:58,041 --> 00:35:02,052
But the only way they can benefit from the exercise is by playing tennis.

286
00:35:03,414 --> 00:35:14,110
So too, we follow the Satipatthana exercises to develop specific skills, tranquility for example, or the ability to see the broader picture.

287
00:35:15,472 --> 00:35:25,628
To reap the benefit, however, we need to relax all effort, return to our main practice of bare attention, being mindful without interfering in any way.

288
00:35:27,469 --> 00:35:32,797
Bare attention allows for insight that leads along the path to the end of suffering.

289
00:35:35,376 --> 00:35:39,963
To finish, let's listen to some of the Sutta's opening lines.

290
00:35:42,347 --> 00:35:56,911
This is the direct path for the purification of beings, for the surmounting of sorrow and lamentation, for the realization of nibbana, namely, the four foundations for mindfulness.

291
00:35:58,545 --> 00:36:03,971
Having gone to the forest or to the root of a tree or to an empty hut, one sits down.

292
00:36:04,911 --> 00:36:11,416
Having folded one's legs crosswise, set the body erect and established mindfulness in front of one.

293
00:36:12,518 --> 00:36:14,699
Ever mindful, one breathes in.

294
00:36:15,659 --> 00:36:17,521
Mindful, one breathes out.

295
00:36:20,545 --> 00:36:28,130
May our practice enable us to surmount sorrow and lamentation, to realize nibbana.

